==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|la|Abderita}}, {{m|la|Abderites}}, from {{der|en|grc|Ἀβδηρίτης}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈæb.dəˌɹaɪt/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An inhabitant or native of [[Abdera]], in [[Thrace]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1814|title=The Historical Library of Diodorus the Sicilian|type=translation|author=G. Booth|volume=2|chapter=4|page=27|passage=To that end they entered the borders of the '''Abderites''' in another part of Thrace, and wasted and spoiled the country {{...}}|by=Diodorus}}
# {{lb|en|‘the Abderite’}} [[Democritus]], the [[laughing|Laughing]] [[philosopher|Philosopher]].

====Usage notes====
Ancient belief was that "the people of Abdera are fools and madmen" (''stulti et insani Abderitae'').<ref>the Latin and English phrases are quoted as they appear in Robert Burton's ''The Anatomy of Melancholy'', volume 1 (2010)</ref>

